After months of conversing with self-identified libertarians on the Internet, I was confused why so many are unable to think critically and hold rational discussions. I couldn't comprehend why someone would go through the trouble of thinking critically and finding their way to libertarianism only to stop thinking critically and begin to think emotionally. I've come to the conclusion that it's because they never came to libertarianism in the first place. They are confused moderates that decided they weren't Republicans or Democrats, so figured that must somehow make them a libertarian. This is why there is so much discord in libertarianism. Because it's filled with confused moderates that know nothing about the philosophy. And sadly, these people now seem to outnumber us.

I love it when someone tries to discredit private roads by saying "I don't want to have to pay a toll every time I go on a road!" Well if the government were in charge of food, would you be saying that we shouldn't privatize the service of providing food because you'd have to pay every time you're hungry? We recognize that capitalism creates competition, which maximizes efficiency and lowers costs. I'd love paying a toll for a road if it meant not having to wait in traffic, not having any potholes, and not being as prone to getting in an accident. Likewise, I love paying for food if it means I can get a juicy double cheeseburger. I'd probably be getting a cube of moldy bread if the government were in charge of food. The government's pothole filled roads are equivalent to that moldy bread.

Small history lesson: The reason the AnCap colors are black and yellow is because black represents "anarchism" and yellow represents "liberalism". I bring this up because liberalism was originally the philosophy of personal and economic liberty. "Liberalism" at its founding was one in the same but eventually split into what we call "Classical Liberalism" (Libertarianism) and "Social Liberalism" (what we call 'Liberal' today). 

You should know this because we have to keep creating new words to define our belief due to the constant infiltration from progressives who wish to pervert the nature of our philosophy.

An example: The libertarian position on gay marriage is not "pro gay marriage", it is that government should stay out of all personal contracts between consenting partners. However many have begun to believe that libertarians believe government should have a positive role in social affairs, which is exactly what liberalism was founded to prevent.

I had to say it so you can point it out when you see it because this is why libertarians infight so much- some care more about equality than they do liberty, and such beliefs get social libertarians like Gary Johnson and William Weld elected nominees at such a crucial point in our election season.

It's unfortunate, but we have to recognize the reality of politics. It's grimy. And until the state is either abolished or minimized to a point where we can easily control it, we must be vociferous in our defense against those that wish to utilize the state to squander our freedoms. If anti-gunners are going to call for a ban on assault weapons in the wake of a tragedy, then we must be equally as loud in our defense of liberty if we wish to preserve it. It is unfortunate that it has to be this way, but if we're not heard, the anti-gunners will be. The American people are looking for a solution, and we have the antidote that they so desperately need. It's called freedom.

Instead of talking about banning guns or banning Islamic immigration, what we need to be talking about is privatizing security. The feds had Omar Mateen in their hands twice and have an expansive data mining program, but were still unable to stop today's attack, once again proving the incompetence of government security. When the government takes control over an industry, it typically runs like the DMV or the post office, with zero efficiency and little incentive to provide a quality service. If we privatize these essential services, competing agencies will have real accountability to their consumers and have an incentive to make sure they are adequately protected.

In the wake of last night's tragedy in Orlando, many Americans will call on our government to trample our freedoms in the name of security. But please be aware of one thing. The government doesn't care about you.

So, as many of you have realized, over the past few weeks we here at Liberty Hangout have come under constant attack for our promotion of presidential candidate Austin Petersen and his limited government proposals. We have been called everything from statists to socialists. However, we welcome the hate, because it is through these strong anti-state feelings that our movement will continue to grow and mature. We are an inclusionary brand. We welcome political and economic birds of all feathers united under the common goal of achieving peace, prosperity, and freedom. We love each and every one of you whether you support us or you do not because we realize libertarianism's founding principle is radical individualism. We respect the sacred nature of the individual and the unique path each person takes in their formation of their sentience and their growth as a living, thinking being. We here at Liberty Hangout do not want power over anyone and we abhor those that do. We are simply using every tool at our disposal to limit, contain, and ultimately abolish the state. Stand with us or stand against us, we will still support you in your pursuits, and you will always have a friend in liberty in us.

I'm not a fan of the ancap argument that "everything government does is constitutional because the Constitution grants them the power to interpret it." This is akin to saying everything a Church does is Biblical, which we know to be patently false since we have the ability to read the Bible and see the disparities for ourselves. In the same way, the framers provide us with the proper context for understanding the original intent of the Constitution. For example, when the 2nd amendment says "a well regulated militia," we can turn to the words of George Mason who said during the Virginia Ratifying Convention, "I ask, sir, what is the militia? It is the whole people, except for a few public officials." It is equally important to note that the Constitution never even granted federal courts the authority to interpret the Constitution on their own accord. The original intent of federal courts was not to interpret the Constitution, but rather to settle disputes between states. The power to interpret the Constitution is not one which was ever expressly given to the courts, but rather a power they usurped themselves. It is therefore false to suggest that everything the government does is Constitutional.

An argument I am often encountered with is that the world would turn chaotic without government. This argument is a faulty one and doesn't take basic praxeology into consideration. Man is naturally self-interested, acts on incentives, and acts at the margin (when marginal benefits outweigh marginal costs). Simply put, man is always looking to improve his living conditions. The cheapest way of accomplishing this is through peaceful and voluntary interactions, otherwise known as free trade. The only other way of improving one's living conditions is through violent crime. What statists fail to realize is that crime is expensive, and the benefits often do not outweigh the costs. If anything, there is greater inventive to commit crime under government since taxes and regulations make it costly to engage in voluntary trade. In the absence of these regulations, engaging in free trade would be cheaper than ever.
